1
00:00:06,306 --> 00:00:09,649
Hello, welcome to another virtual talk.

2
00:00:09,649 --> 00:00:12,491
This is Cutting Apart the Diegetic Interface

3
00:00:12,491 --> 00:00:14,893
of Hardspace Shipbreaker.

4
00:00:14,893 --> 00:00:18,375
I am Vidhi, a game and UX designer from Vancouver, Canada.

5
00:00:19,096 --> 00:00:21,538
and I'm currently working at Blackbird Interactive.

6
00:00:21,538 --> 00:00:24,299
I've been with the studio for over two years now,

7
00:00:24,299 --> 00:00:27,542
and in my time, I have worked on a couple of different projects,

8
00:00:27,542 --> 00:00:30,403
the first one being Minecraft Earth.

9
00:00:30,403 --> 00:00:32,745
On that project, I was a UX designer,

10
00:00:32,745 --> 00:00:35,687
and currently, I work on Hardspace Shipbreaker

11
00:00:35,687 --> 00:00:36,788
as a game and UX designer.

12
00:00:38,703 --> 00:00:41,825
Today I'll be talking about Hardspace Shipbreaker's

13
00:00:41,825 --> 00:00:46,148
recent UI redesign and how we made a decision

14
00:00:46,148 --> 00:00:49,050
on our design approach and how we landed on it.

15
00:00:49,050 --> 00:00:52,092
I'll talk about our approaches application

16
00:00:52,092 --> 00:00:55,495
on a handful of screens, the HUD, the death experience

17
00:00:55,495 --> 00:00:57,576
and the habitation module.

18
00:00:57,576 --> 00:00:59,598
I'll also discuss the challenges faced

19
00:00:59,598 --> 00:01:02,340
and finally the learning outcomes in the game

20
00:01:02,340 --> 00:01:03,901
and from this experience.

21
00:01:06,293 --> 00:01:13,398
For those who don't know, Hardspace Shipbreaker is an award-winning physics game where you play as a blue-collar worker in space,

22
00:01:13,398 --> 00:01:17,701
where you're cutting apart and salvaging ships, all while being in zero-g.

23
00:01:17,701 --> 00:01:23,444
We're a fairly small team of about 30 people and have been in early access for over a year now,

24
00:01:23,444 --> 00:01:26,186
and that's how long I have been on this project.

25
00:01:26,186 --> 00:01:30,949
Like everyone on the team, I too have to wear multiple hats.

26
00:01:31,767 --> 00:01:33,708
And I've been a part of the game's design

27
00:01:33,708 --> 00:01:35,770
in a handful of different disciplines,

28
00:01:35,770 --> 00:01:36,570
UX, game, and narrative design.

29
00:01:36,570 --> 00:01:38,351
This game is one of the first of its kind

30
00:01:38,351 --> 00:01:39,352
and it has carved its own genre.

31
00:01:39,352 --> 00:01:42,094
So let's look at the game.

32
00:01:42,094 --> 00:01:42,894
My name is Weaver.

33
00:01:42,894 --> 00:01:45,636
I'll be your eyes and ears when you're in the yard.

34
00:01:45,636 --> 00:01:47,877
Used to be a cutter myself

35
00:01:47,877 --> 00:01:57,243
until there were some complications.

36
00:02:04,065 --> 00:02:16,188
Let's get to work.

37
00:02:52,841 --> 00:02:59,286
So narratively, this game is set in the future, where Earth is in a pretty bad shape and humans

38
00:02:59,286 --> 00:03:04,850
have terraformed and moved over to other planets. Since you can't quite afford a ticket to safer

39
00:03:04,850 --> 00:03:10,974
planets, you take on this job with Lynx, which is an evil corporation. You take on a job as

40
00:03:10,974 --> 00:03:14,557
the salvager or cutter and it comes with a hefty debt.

41
00:03:15,248 --> 00:03:19,411
So with each ship that you salvage, you essentially pay off your debt.

42
00:03:19,411 --> 00:03:24,455
Now of course, there's endless fines and fees that you have to pay to live, and they just

43
00:03:24,455 --> 00:03:29,940
kind of keep piling up, but I mean, what else do you expect from an evil company that's

44
00:03:29,940 --> 00:03:32,622
all about capitalism and profits?

45
00:03:32,622 --> 00:03:35,284
So let's get into the game.

46
00:03:35,284 --> 00:03:40,228
When you begin the game, the first thing a player experiences is this contract screen.

47
00:03:40,228 --> 00:03:42,811
It's perhaps one of my favorite experiences in the game.

48
00:03:43,844 --> 00:03:47,248
Similar to forms that you may have filled in your life,

49
00:03:47,248 --> 00:03:50,311
you're filling out another corporate bone dry piece

50
00:03:50,311 --> 00:03:51,653
of paperwork.

51
00:03:51,653 --> 00:03:56,378
Set in this cold, damp looking room, you sign your life away.

52
00:03:56,378 --> 00:03:58,881
You never really read the terms and conditions.

53
00:03:58,881 --> 00:04:00,103
You look at your food options.

54
00:04:00,103 --> 00:04:01,444
They're all quite dismal.

55
00:04:02,468 --> 00:04:05,411
But this interaction immediately sets the tone

56
00:04:05,411 --> 00:04:09,656
for the rest of the game world, which is it's dark,

57
00:04:09,656 --> 00:04:13,620
it's corporate, and it's so real that it kind of hurts.

58
00:04:13,620 --> 00:04:17,263
So this experience became the template

59
00:04:17,263 --> 00:04:20,727
or the standard of the experience that we wanted to apply

60
00:04:20,727 --> 00:04:22,829
to the rest of the screens in the game,

61
00:04:22,829 --> 00:04:25,471
which in the form when I joined the team wasn't the case.

62
00:04:27,220 --> 00:04:29,261
So while preparing for the redesign,

63
00:04:29,261 --> 00:04:33,224
the first thing we had to identify were the constraints.

64
00:04:33,224 --> 00:04:35,186
The first one is short timelines.

65
00:04:35,186 --> 00:04:37,507
Since we are in early access,

66
00:04:37,507 --> 00:04:40,449
our release cycles range anywhere

67
00:04:40,449 --> 00:04:42,191
between one to three months,

68
00:04:42,191 --> 00:04:45,973
which is not a whole lot of time to make large changes,

69
00:04:45,973 --> 00:04:49,996
while you're also making changes to other facets of the game

70
00:04:49,996 --> 00:04:52,258
like tools, ship, and tech.

71
00:04:52,258 --> 00:04:53,719
So we had limited dev time

72
00:04:53,719 --> 00:04:56,301
when we were looking at the UI redesign.

73
00:04:56,711 --> 00:04:59,793
We also had limited design time.

74
00:04:59,793 --> 00:05:03,776
I was the only person kind of in charge of this revamp,

75
00:05:03,776 --> 00:05:05,978
and I was also in charge of other things in the game,

76
00:05:05,978 --> 00:05:08,199
just like everybody else on this team.

77
00:05:08,199 --> 00:05:10,141
So we had to be strategic

78
00:05:10,141 --> 00:05:12,282
with how we approached this redesign

79
00:05:12,282 --> 00:05:15,004
and how much time and effort and resources

80
00:05:15,004 --> 00:05:16,285
we could put behind it.

81
00:05:17,507 --> 00:05:20,509
Now, the game is set in a pretty interesting and expansive world,

82
00:05:20,509 --> 00:05:23,070
as I just kind of mentioned before.

83
00:05:23,070 --> 00:05:26,672
But with our releases, we're introducing the story

84
00:05:26,672 --> 00:05:28,593
and other characters into this world.

85
00:05:28,593 --> 00:05:31,095
And we're doing this mostly through talking heads

86
00:05:31,095 --> 00:05:35,497
or very text-heavy messages that players receive in the game.

87
00:05:36,197 --> 00:05:37,978
And this is because of our limited resources.

88
00:05:37,978 --> 00:05:41,779
We don't have a budget for cut scenes, quick time events,

89
00:05:41,779 --> 00:05:47,041
3D modeled characters that could potentially be animated.

90
00:05:47,041 --> 00:05:50,002
So we realized that the UI would have

91
00:05:50,002 --> 00:05:53,824
to do a lot of the world building heavy lifting.

92
00:05:53,824 --> 00:05:56,204
And that led to the challenge.

93
00:05:56,204 --> 00:06:00,046
How do we add depth to the story through the game's UI?

94
00:06:01,612 --> 00:06:04,674
We wanted to not only redesign the interface

95
00:06:04,674 --> 00:06:09,458
to make it more usable, it was very much made by devs

96
00:06:09,458 --> 00:06:12,700
in the past, but we wanted to make the experience

97
00:06:12,700 --> 00:06:16,222
more immersive and embedded into the game world.

98
00:06:16,222 --> 00:06:18,844
We wanted to build a mental space for the player,

99
00:06:18,844 --> 00:06:21,125
for this company that they're working for,

100
00:06:21,125 --> 00:06:22,726
and the world that this game is set in

101
00:06:22,726 --> 00:06:24,528
all through the game's UI.

102
00:06:24,928 --> 00:06:30,913
So that's the kind of the point of this talk, is to show how you can accomplish or what you

103
00:06:30,913 --> 00:06:36,818
can accomplish when user experience design, game design, and narrative collaborate from

104
00:06:36,818 --> 00:06:44,104
the very beginning to find inexpensive solutions to building a game world. In our case, this was

105
00:06:44,104 --> 00:06:45,406
purely an outcome of necessity.

106
00:06:46,739 --> 00:06:50,261
because of our limited resources, as I just mentioned,

107
00:06:50,261 --> 00:06:52,862
but it helped us understand and finalize our approach,

108
00:06:52,862 --> 00:06:56,243
which is a mostly diegetic approach to the game UI.

109
00:06:56,243 --> 00:06:58,584
And I'll kind of expand on that throughout the talk.

110
00:06:58,584 --> 00:07:00,845
But what we really wanted to do

111
00:07:00,845 --> 00:07:03,126
was use every screen in the game

112
00:07:03,126 --> 00:07:05,247
or every opportunity in the game

113
00:07:05,247 --> 00:07:07,267
to build a sense of presence for the player

114
00:07:07,267 --> 00:07:09,328
and make it more immersive.

115
00:07:09,328 --> 00:07:11,529
Now, I might interchange between those two terms,

116
00:07:11,529 --> 00:07:12,790
game presence and immersion,

117
00:07:12,790 --> 00:07:14,530
but this is what I'm really referring to.

118
00:07:15,873 --> 00:07:18,558
For those who don't know, diegetic is a term used across media,

119
00:07:18,558 --> 00:07:23,707
and what it really means is an element that exists.

120
00:07:23,973 --> 00:07:28,775
both for the audience or the player, as well as the characters within the world.

121
00:07:28,775 --> 00:07:35,319
It's one of the four types of UI in games, and we heavily leaned upon this UI style.

122
00:07:35,319 --> 00:07:41,743
So from the example before, the contract screen is not just a 2D UI element,

123
00:07:41,743 --> 00:07:45,505
but it's rather contextually and physically placed in the game world,

124
00:07:45,505 --> 00:07:50,127
where both you as the player and the character in the game world interact with this interface.

125
00:07:51,901 --> 00:07:55,744
We identified four pillars that we wanted to take

126
00:07:55,744 --> 00:07:57,786
or hit with our design approach.

127
00:07:57,786 --> 00:07:59,888
First one being information architecture.

128
00:07:59,888 --> 00:08:02,070
This game is very information-dense

129
00:08:02,070 --> 00:08:05,513
and all mostly condensed into a single screen,

130
00:08:05,513 --> 00:08:08,276
and it often became a point of contention for our players.

131
00:08:08,276 --> 00:08:10,958
So we wanted to ensure we built a clear hierarchy.

132
00:08:10,958 --> 00:08:15,463
We wanted to make large amounts of information digestible.

133
00:08:16,471 --> 00:08:18,132
The second being gameplay.

134
00:08:18,132 --> 00:08:20,773
So we wanted to use these screens to direct players

135
00:08:20,773 --> 00:08:23,175
to complete or hit design goals in the game.

136
00:08:23,175 --> 00:08:28,297
As the game is developed, so have the goals within the game.

137
00:08:28,297 --> 00:08:31,919
So we had to work as a unit, all designers together,

138
00:08:31,919 --> 00:08:33,580
to identify these new goals

139
00:08:33,580 --> 00:08:35,521
and how we can guide the players

140
00:08:35,521 --> 00:08:38,883
to those goals through the UI.

141
00:08:38,883 --> 00:08:40,944
Usability, bit of a no-brainer

142
00:08:40,944 --> 00:08:43,625
as someone who is looking at interfaces day in, day out.

143
00:08:45,074 --> 00:08:47,756
We obviously wanted to hit some of the basics,

144
00:08:47,756 --> 00:08:52,260
readability, usability, and navigation,

145
00:08:52,260 --> 00:08:54,662
but this is really not a usability talk,

146
00:08:54,662 --> 00:08:56,404
and I don't want to focus on that.

147
00:08:56,404 --> 00:08:58,986
What I really want to talk about is integrating

148
00:08:58,986 --> 00:09:02,689
that last element of the story and the narrative in.

149
00:09:02,689 --> 00:09:06,092
What we really wanted to do was build game presence

150
00:09:06,092 --> 00:09:10,296
through the game's interface, and that's the approach,

151
00:09:10,296 --> 00:09:13,178
and that's the real point of this talk today.

152
00:09:15,070 --> 00:09:17,272
Now to take this approach, two sections of design

153
00:09:17,272 --> 00:09:20,434
had to work together, one impacting the other

154
00:09:20,434 --> 00:09:21,274
and vice versa.

155
00:09:21,274 --> 00:09:25,457
Oftentimes, they are two separate factions in a studio

156
00:09:25,457 --> 00:09:28,779
and they don't get to be so closely integrated.

157
00:09:28,779 --> 00:09:31,940
So I thought I would be very much like the Spider-Man,

158
00:09:31,940 --> 00:09:33,501
pulling these two ends together.

159
00:09:33,501 --> 00:09:34,302
I'm so cool.

160
00:09:34,302 --> 00:09:35,523
I'm so smart and strong.

161
00:09:35,523 --> 00:09:38,164
But in reality, that's kind of what

162
00:09:38,164 --> 00:09:40,045
my experience was mostly like.

163
00:09:40,045 --> 00:09:41,466
I definitely felt like that cat.

164
00:09:43,704 --> 00:09:45,605
And I especially felt like this cat

165
00:09:45,605 --> 00:09:48,786
when we were addressing the densest screen of our game.

166
00:09:48,786 --> 00:09:53,528
And that game, and that screen, sorry, is the HUD.

167
00:09:53,528 --> 00:09:56,389
So before I show you what we got to, where we are today,

168
00:09:56,389 --> 00:09:59,991
let's look at the very first HUD of the game.

169
00:09:59,991 --> 00:10:02,892
Because this HUD set the seed

170
00:10:02,892 --> 00:10:04,353
for the rest of the experiences.

171
00:10:04,353 --> 00:10:07,814
So what you're seeing here is the first prototype

172
00:10:07,814 --> 00:10:08,474
of the game.

173
00:10:08,474 --> 00:10:11,596
It was an outcome of a game jam within the studio.

174
00:10:12,280 --> 00:10:17,304
What you're seeing on this HUD is something that's truly diegetic.

175
00:10:17,304 --> 00:10:20,667
As the player's head moves around,

176
00:10:20,667 --> 00:10:24,551
the camera moves to mimic your head shaking or your head moving around.

177
00:10:24,551 --> 00:10:26,213
And I'll kind of play this again for you to see.

178
00:10:27,498 --> 00:10:29,439
Of course, it's a little janky. It's a prototype.

179
00:10:29,439 --> 00:10:31,721
But theoretically, it's very cool. It's very novel.

180
00:10:31,721 --> 00:10:35,384
But it definitely has some obvious usability concerns.

181
00:10:35,384 --> 00:10:37,446
You have UI components being cut off.

182
00:10:37,446 --> 00:10:39,628
You have text kind of being burnt on the edges.

183
00:10:39,628 --> 00:10:45,333
And this would be considered a truly diegetic approach, right?

184
00:10:45,333 --> 00:10:50,697
Something that is the suit that is on the helmet

185
00:10:50,697 --> 00:10:52,358
of the suit of the cutter.

186
00:10:52,358 --> 00:10:54,600
It's on that glass, and it's kind of displayed

187
00:10:54,600 --> 00:10:55,441
onto this glass.

188
00:10:56,465 --> 00:10:59,948
So as much as we walked away from this concept

189
00:10:59,948 --> 00:11:01,310
because of usability reasons

190
00:11:01,310 --> 00:11:04,053
and the amount of information we'll have to show,

191
00:11:04,053 --> 00:11:06,816
this seed was set pretty early on.

192
00:11:06,816 --> 00:11:10,219
It had to be a helmet,

193
00:11:10,219 --> 00:11:12,221
and it had to be displayed on that glass.

194
00:11:12,221 --> 00:11:16,306
This is the HUD that the game launched with.

195
00:11:16,306 --> 00:11:18,388
It is not the HUD that you have in the game today.

196
00:11:19,227 --> 00:11:21,749
What you're seeing is you in the bay.

197
00:11:21,749 --> 00:11:24,250
This is where majority of the gameplay takes place.

198
00:11:24,250 --> 00:11:27,012
You're holding a grapple, or you'd be holding another tool,

199
00:11:27,012 --> 00:11:31,415
and you begin cutting, or you begin salvaging.

200
00:11:31,415 --> 00:11:34,817
The HUD is still a display on the helmet,

201
00:11:34,817 --> 00:11:37,199
but it's less responsive to movement,

202
00:11:37,199 --> 00:11:38,980
as we just saw in the example before.

203
00:11:38,980 --> 00:11:42,082
The biggest difference between these two screens,

204
00:11:42,082 --> 00:11:44,123
and of course, the styling difference isn't a whole lot,

205
00:11:44,123 --> 00:11:47,425
but the main thing I want you to focus on

206
00:11:47,425 --> 00:11:48,766
is the amount of information.

207
00:11:49,260 --> 00:11:53,122
packed onto the screen in a single interface.

208
00:11:53,122 --> 00:12:02,205
And I want to walk you through the four pillars that we had

209
00:12:02,205 --> 00:12:03,846
and how we address them in this HUD.

210
00:12:03,846 --> 00:12:07,627
But first, let's look at all the information on the screen.

211
00:12:09,412 --> 00:12:11,514
So, in this situation, you're inside of a ship

212
00:12:11,514 --> 00:12:13,376
and you're cutting,

213
00:12:13,376 --> 00:12:17,660
and the biggest UI element you're seeing is this work order.

214
00:12:17,660 --> 00:12:19,883
It tells the player what they need to salvage

215
00:12:19,883 --> 00:12:21,964
when they're in a particular shift,

216
00:12:21,964 --> 00:12:24,947
and it takes the majority of your screen space.

217
00:12:25,785 --> 00:12:30,489
Here you're seeing your tool information displayed in four vastly different locations,

218
00:12:30,489 --> 00:12:33,471
even though it all pertains to the single tool that you have in your hand.

219
00:12:33,471 --> 00:12:38,575
The temperature, the durability, the ability to navigate to other tools,

220
00:12:38,575 --> 00:12:42,638
and on the top left, you're seeing the tether count,

221
00:12:42,638 --> 00:12:47,422
or it would be the demo charge count, depending on the tool in your hand.

222
00:12:47,422 --> 00:12:50,584
But to see information about a single object,

223
00:12:50,584 --> 00:12:55,088
a player would have to look kind of all the way around the screen to gather that information.

224
00:12:55,734 --> 00:12:58,535
not particularly ideal.

225
00:12:58,535 --> 00:13:03,136
Here you see highlighted your stats, your oxygen meter,

226
00:13:03,136 --> 00:13:06,137
and the timer of your shift.

227
00:13:06,137 --> 00:13:10,758
Some of these elements need to be replenished multiple times

228
00:13:10,758 --> 00:13:11,439
within a shift.

229
00:13:11,439 --> 00:13:13,399
They're quite vital and important for a player

230
00:13:13,399 --> 00:13:17,140
to look at when it comes to moment-to-moment gameplay.

231
00:13:17,401 --> 00:13:20,524
And questionably, some of the more important UI components

232
00:13:20,524 --> 00:13:23,487
are these two, where you have your object information,

233
00:13:23,487 --> 00:13:27,252
where a salvage item goes, and the pressurization state

234
00:13:27,252 --> 00:13:28,072
of a room.

235
00:13:28,072 --> 00:13:29,494
That's important.

236
00:13:29,494 --> 00:13:32,217
If you begin cutting in a pressurized room,

237
00:13:32,217 --> 00:13:34,520
you will blow up and die.

238
00:13:34,520 --> 00:13:35,721
So don't do that.

239
00:13:35,721 --> 00:13:36,061
Not good.

240
00:13:38,030 --> 00:13:41,151
And the last thing I want to kind of bring focus to here

241
00:13:41,151 --> 00:13:42,331
is the subtitles.

242
00:13:42,331 --> 00:13:45,632
You'll see them overlaid on top of other UI elements,

243
00:13:45,632 --> 00:13:48,833
making neither the UI elements nor the subtitles

244
00:13:48,833 --> 00:13:50,894
particularly legible.

245
00:13:50,894 --> 00:13:54,114
What I haven't even done here is highlight the notifications,

246
00:13:54,114 --> 00:13:56,875
the hazard warnings, and other UI elements

247
00:13:56,875 --> 00:13:59,716
that appear on the screen from time to time.

248
00:14:01,062 --> 00:14:03,922
But the idea I'm trying to kind of convey across

249
00:14:03,922 --> 00:14:06,563
is that there's a lot of information on this one screen,

250
00:14:06,563 --> 00:14:10,543
and it is scattered, and there is no clear hierarchy.

251
00:14:10,543 --> 00:14:12,784
So this is the new HUD.

